Otahuhu||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|12||McGee||City Rovers||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|12||Wrightson||Otahuhu||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n|}\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:1915 in New Zealand rugby league|Auckland Rugby League]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup|reason=drop caps as per [[MOS:HEADINGS]]|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\nThe 1915 season, and 7th of [[Auckland Rugby League]] saw the First Grade competition begin on 8 May featuring the same 6 senior clubs who had competed in 1914.\n\nThe [[First World War]] was in full effect by the time the 1915 season began. War had been declared just as the 1914 rugby league season was concluding in August 1914. As a result, several efforts were made during the 1915 season by the [[Auckland Rugby League]] to raise funds for Auckland Hospital Ship and Wounded Soldiers Relief Fund.\n\nOn 12 June, a seven-a-side tournament was arranged to be played at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] to raise money for the Auckland Hospital Ship and Wounded Relief Fund.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Patriotic Tournament\n| page =8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LII| issue=15937\n| date = 7 July 1915\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150607.2.60| accessdate = 13 August 2019}}</ref> In total \u00a3200 was raised with \"almost 1,000 people\" in attendance. All senior clubs entered teams and the final was played between [[North Shore Albions]] and [[City Rovers]] though the match was not completed owing to the fact that some earlier matches went to extra-time and the final saw an injury requiring a stoppage. As it had become dark it was decided to call the game off with [[North Shore Albions|North Shore]] leading by 3pts.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Seven-A-Side Tournament\n| page =8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LII| issue=15943\n| date = 14 July 1915\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150614.2.108\n| accessdate = 13 August 2019}}</ref> A further \u00a335 was raised from the 19 June round of matches at Victoria Park for the same cause.\n\n[[Grafton Athletic]] were crowned First Grade champions for the first time after defeating [[City Rovers]] 10\u20135 in the championship final at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] in front of 4,000 spectators.\n\n==The Beginning of the Roope Rooster==\nA trophy which is still played for today saw its beginnings in the 1915 season. Namely the Roope Rooster trophy which was donated by Mr. R Roope. It was a knockout competition with one round of matches before semi-finals were played.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Knock-Out Round/Wins for Grafton, Shore, and Newton\n| page =7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLVI| issue=188\n| date = 9 August 1915\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19150809.2.94.2\n| accessdate = 13 August 2019}}</ref> With the semi-final between Newton and Grafton being drawn (after North Shore received the bye) the management committee decided rather than replaying a match between the same teams there would be more interest in a match between Grafton and North Shore, with Newton progressing to the final. The second semi-final was played at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] and saw both teams wearing white armbands in memory of 3 men killed in action at the [[Dardanelles]] who had played club rugby league in Auckland ([[Charles Savory]] from [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], Charles James Hally from [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]], and William Moeki from [[City Rovers]]).<ref>{{cite news \n| title =North Shore Defeats Grafton/North Shore's Surprise\n| page =8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LII| issue=16003\n| date = 23 August 1915\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150823.2.96.1\n| accessdate = 13 August 2019}}</ref> A charge was made for the semi-final between North Shore and Grafton with the proceeds going to the Door of Hope, the Salvation Army Maternity and Rescue Homes, Sister Esther's Relief Work, and the St John Ambulance Brigade. The final was played on 11 September at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] between [[North Shore Albions]] and [[Newton Rangers]], with [[North Shore Albions|North Shore]] winning 10 points to 7.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Roope's Rooster/Won by North Shore\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LII| issue=16021\n| date = 13 September 1915\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150913.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n    {{s-bef|before=[[1914 Auckland Rugby League season|1914]]}}\n    {{s-ttl|title=7th [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n    |years=1915}}\n    {{s-aft|after=[[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916]]}}\n    {{end}}\n\n==Obituaries==\n===Charles Savory===\nCharles Savory was born on 23 March 1889 and grew up in Auckland. In 1910 he was suspended from playing rugby for two years for kicking an opponent and he switched to rugby league where he joined the Ponsonby team. Savory played for Ponsonby United from 1911 to 1914 and scored 16 tries and kicked 13 goals. For Auckland he played 4 times, scoring 3 tries and kicking 11 goals all in the 1914 season. He had made a quick impression after switching codes and was selected to play for the touring New Zealand side on their visit to Australia. He was then selected for the 1911\u201312 tour of the United Kingdom for the Australasian side. In 1912 he was sent off in a club match versus Newton which meant he was unable to tour with the New Zealand team to Australia. In 1913 he was accused of injuring a player from Manukau and was banned for life however on appeal the New Zealand Council refused to confirm the ban and ultimately sacked the entire Auckland Rugby League board and selected a new one.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Football Incident\n| page =10\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLIV| issue=153\n| date = 28 June 1913\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19130628.2.77\n| accessdate = 12 August 2019}}</ref> Savory was also an outstanding boxer and in 1914 he became the National Amateur Heavyweight Boxing champion. In 1915 he enlisted in the army and on 8 May 1915 he was killed by a shell to the head before he reached shore at the Dardanelles aged 26.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Death of C. Savory/International Footballer Killed/Belated Notification\n| page =6\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLVI| issue=194\n| date = 16 August 1915\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19150816.2.47\n| accessdate = 14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===William Moeki===\nWilliam Moeki was born at Port Awanui on the East Coast. He was also known as W\u0101tene Moeke and William Moeke. He played for the [[City Rovers]] from 1911 to 1914 in the forwards and scored 8 tries. He joined the Auckland Infantry Battalion and embarked for [[Suez]], [[Egypt]] on 16 October 1914. William Moeki was killed in action at the [[Dardanelles]] on 25 April 1915. In a letter back to New Zealand by well known Auckland boxer Private Alfred Gault, Moeki was said to have last been seen in a bayonet charge.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Soldiers' Letters/In the Trenches at the Dardanelles/A Well Told Story\n| page =2\n| work=[[Auckland Star]] |volume=XLVI |issue=155\n| date = 1 July 1911\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19150701.2.10\n| accessdate = 9 December 2019}}</ref> His name is memorialised on the [[Lone Pine Memorial]], at Lone Pine Cemetery in [[Anzac Cove]], [[Turkey]] and at Tikitiki Church's War Memorial.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Memorial at Lonepine Cemetery\n| page =1\n| publisher =Auckland Museum\n| date = 18 January 2020\n| url =https://www.aucklandmuseum.com/war-memorial/online-cenotaph/record/C10868\n| accessdate = 18 January 2019}}</ref> He was awarded the 1914\u20131915 Star, and British War & Victory Medals.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =William Moeki\n| page =1\n| publisher =Auckland Museum\n| date = 18 January 2020\n| url =https://www.aucklandmuseum.com/war-memorial/online-cenotaph/record/C10868\n| accessdate = 18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Charles James Hally===\nCharles James Hally was born on 18 May 1889 in [[Cambridge, New Zealand]]. Hally was also an outstanding sprinter and in 1913 was runner-up in the 100 and 220-yard championships of New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Athletics\n| page =16\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XLVI| issue=193\n| date = 14 August 1915\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19150814.2.162.9\n| accessdate = 18 January 2020}}</ref> In 1914 he had moved to Auckland and played for the [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]] senior team where he scored 2 tries. He had moved to [[Morrinsville]] where he was farming before enlisting in the army soon after the outbreak of the war on 11 August 1914. He was injured in battle on 8 May in an attack on the Daisy Patch at Gallipoli and recovered on [[RMS Franconia (1910)|Hospital Ship Franconia]] and at [[Cairo]] once ashore. He again joined the battle on the attack at Courtnays Post, Gallipoli serving in the Hauraki Company of the Auckland Infantry however this time he was wounded more seriously in the lungs and legs and succumbed to his injuries on 26 July 1915. He was buried at sea off [[Kabatepe|Gaba Tepe]]. Like William Moeki he is commemorated at the [[Lone Pine Memorial]] in Anzac, [[Turkey]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Charles James Hally\n| page =1\n| publisher =Cambridge High School\n| date = 18 January 2020\n| url =http://www.camhigh.school.nz/old_boys/page/Students/hally_cj.html\n| accessdate = 18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==First Grade Championship==\nTwenty eight matches were played in the first grade competition. Nine full rounds were played followed by the final. [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] was the main ground used, with matches also played at the [[Auckland Domain]], [[Devonport Domain]], and [[Otahuhu]].\n\n===Final Standings===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Grafton Athletic]]\n|10||7||1||2||118||70||'''15'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|10||6||1||3||93||63||'''13'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|9||5||1||3||93||63||'''11'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions]]\n|9||4||1||4||76||83||'''9'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|9||3||0||6||80||118||'''6'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]]\n|9||1||0||8||48||111||'''2'''\n|-\n|}\n\n===First Grade Fixtures===\n===Round 1===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 8 May\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 15\u20130\n| report =<ref name=\"herald\">{{cite news\n| title =Grafton Beats Ponsonby/City's Easy Win/The Champions Extended\n| page =11\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LII| issue=15913\n| date = 10 May 1915\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150510.2.134.2\n| accessdate = 12 August 2019}}</ref>\n| away = Newton\n| try1 = V Bachard, Harold Denize, Brooks, [[Jim Rukutai]], Davidson\n| con1 =\n| pen1 =\n| try2 =\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance =\n| referee = Vance\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 8 May\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Ponsonby\n| score = 2\u201311\n| report =<ref name=\"herald\" />| away = Grafton\n| try1 = \n| con1 = \n| pen1 = [[Charles Webb (rugby league)|Charles Webb]]\n| try2 = A McGregor\n| con2 = [[Karl Ifwersen]]\n| pen2 = [[Karl Ifwersen]] 2 & a mark\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance =\n| referee = J Fielding\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 8